{"format": "tiptap/v1", "doc": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The Core Idea: Words as Vectors"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Word2Vec (Mikolov et al., 2013) learns dense vector representations of words by training a shallow neural network to predict words from their neighbours. The learned vectors, called embeddings, capture semantic relationships: vectors for similar words end up close together, and arithmetic like "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "king − man + woman ≈ queen"}, {"type": "text", "text": " emerges naturally from the training objective."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Word2Vec offers two architectures. Both process a sliding window over a corpus and produce the same type of output — a weight matrix whose rows are word vectors — but they frame the prediction problem differently."}]}, {"type": "image", "attrs": {"src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,", "alt": "CBOW (left): four context words are averaged into a hidden embedding that predicts the center word 'sat'. Skip-gram (right): the center word 'sat' is projected to an embedding that predicts each of the four context words independently. Comparison table shows CBOW is faster, Skip-gram handles rare words better."}}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "CBOW — Continuous Bag of Words"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "CBOW takes the context words (the surrounding window) as input and predicts the center word. The context word vectors are averaged before the softmax output layer, which is why rare words tend to be diluted — their signal is mixed with the more frequent neighbours."}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "For a window of size 2 around the center word "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "w"}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "t"}, {"type": "text", "text": ":"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "\\hat{v} = \\frac{1}{4}\\left(v_{t-2} + v_{t-1} + v_{t+1} + v_{t+2}\\right)"}}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The model maximises "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "P(w_t | w_{t-2}, w_{t-1}, w_{t+1}, w_{t+2})"}, {"type": "text", "text": " using the averaged vector as input to a softmax over the full vocabulary."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Skip-gram"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Skip-gram reverses the task: given a center word, predict each surrounding context word independently. For a center word "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "w"}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "t"}, {"type": "text", "text": " the objective is:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "\\mathcal{L} = -\\sum_{-c \\le j \\le c, j \\ne 0} \\log P(w_{t+j} \\mid w_t)"}}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Because each context word generates a separate training signal for the center word, Skip-gram produces more training examples per token. This makes it slower but gives better representations for rare words — each rare word still gets dedicated gradient updates rather than being averaged away."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Negative Sampling"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Computing softmax over the full vocabulary (often 100 000+ words) is expensive. Negative sampling replaces it with binary classification: for each positive (word, context) pair, sample "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "k"}, {"type": "text", "text": " random \"negative\" words and train the model to distinguish real pairs from noise. The objective becomes:"}]}, {"type": "blockMath", "attrs": {"latex": "\\mathcal{L} = \\log \\sigma(v_{w_O}^\\top v_{w_I}) + \\sum_{i=1}^{k} \\mathbb{E}_{w_i \\sim P_n(w)} \\left[\\log \\sigma(-v_{w_i}^\\top v_{w_I})\\right]"}}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Negative words are sampled from the unigram distribution raised to the 3/4 power, which boosts rare words slightly. In practice "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "italic"}], "text": "k"}, {"type": "text", "text": " = 5–20 for small corpora, 2–5 for large ones."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Training Word2Vec with Gensim"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "# pip install gensim\nfrom gensim.models import Word2Vec\n\n# Corpus: list of tokenised sentences\nsentences = [\n    [\"the\", \"cat\", \"sat\", \"on\", \"the\", \"mat\"],\n    [\"the\", \"dog\", \"lay\", \"on\", \"the\", \"rug\"],\n    [\"cats\", \"and\", \"dogs\", \"are\", \"common\", \"pets\"],\n    # ... typically millions of sentences\n]\n\nmodel = Word2Vec(\n    sentences,\n    vector_size=100,   # embedding dimensions\n    window=5,          # context window size each side\n    min_count=1,       # ignore words with fewer occurrences\n    sg=1,              # 0 = CBOW, 1 = Skip-gram\n    negative=5,        # number of negative samples\n    epochs=10,\n    workers=4,\n)\n\n# Access the embedding for a word\nprint(model.wv[\"cat\"])          # shape (100,)\nprint(model.wv.similarity(\"cat\", \"dog\"))   # cosine similarity\nprint(model.wv.most_similar(\"cat\", topn=3))"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Analogy arithmetic"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "# king - man + woman ≈ ?\nresult = model.wv.most_similar(\n    positive=[\"king\", \"woman\"],\n    negative=[\"man\"],\n    topn=1,\n)\nprint(result)   # [('queen', 0.87)] on a large trained corpus"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Loading Pretrained Vectors"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "For most projects there is no reason to train from scratch. Google's pretrained Word2Vec model (3 billion words, 300-dimensional, 3 million word vocabulary) is available as a binary file:"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "from gensim.models import KeyedVectors\n\n# Download GoogleNews-vectors-negative300.bin.gz from the Word2Vec project page\nwv = KeyedVectors.load_word2vec_format(\n    \"GoogleNews-vectors-negative300.bin\",\n    binary=True,\n)\n\nprint(wv[\"python\"].shape)          # (300,)\nprint(wv.most_similar(\"python\", topn=5))\n# [('ruby', 0.76), ('perl', 0.75), ('php', 0.73), ...]"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Alternatively, use Hugging Face's "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "gensim-data"}, {"type": "text", "text": " downloader:"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import gensim.downloader as api\n\nwv = api.load(\"word2vec-google-news-300\")   # ~1.7 GB download, cached\nprint(wv.similarity(\"france\", \"paris\"))     # 0.78"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Key Hyperparameters"}]}, {"type": "table", "content": [{"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Parameter"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Typical value"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Effect"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "vector_size"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "100–300"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Larger → richer representations, slower training"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "window"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "5"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Smaller → syntactic similarity; larger → topical similarity"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "negative"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "5–20"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "More negatives → better quality, slower"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "min_count"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "5"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Discard rare words with fewer occurrences"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "code"}], "text": "sg"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "1 (Skip-gram)"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "0 = CBOW (faster); 1 = Skip-gram (better for rare words)"}]}]}]}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Limitations"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "One vector per word-type"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": \"bank\" (financial) and \"bank\" (river) share the same vector. Context is ignored at inference time."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Out-of-vocabulary words"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": words not seen during training have no vector. FastText solves this with character n-grams."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Bias in training data"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": embeddings mirror biases in the source corpus (e.g. gendered profession associations)."}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "No subword information"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": morphologically related words (\"run\", \"running\", \"ran\") get unrelated vectors unless seen frequently together."}]}]}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "These limitations motivated contextual embeddings (ELMo, BERT) and subword-aware models (FastText, SentencePiece), which are covered in the next sub-subtopics."}]}]}}